Step 3 (Recommended for prod safety): Create a read-only ServiceAccount
Since you manage prod EKS clusters, don't point this at your full admin kubeconfig. Create a scoped one:

apiVersion: v1
kind: ServiceAccount
metadata:
  name: claude-readonly
  namespace: default
---
apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
kind: ClusterRole
metadata:
  name: claude-viewer
rules:
- apiGroups: [""]
  resources: ["pods", "services", "events", "pods/log"]
  verbs: ["get", "list", "watch"]
- apiGroups: ["apps"]
  resources: ["deployments", "replicasets"]
  verbs: ["get", "list", "watch"]
---
apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
kind: ClusterRoleBinding
metadata:
  name: claude-viewer-binding
subjects:
- kind: ServiceAccount
  name: claude-readonly
  namespace: default
roleRef:
  kind: ClusterRole
  name: claude-viewer
  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io

Apply it, then generate a kubeconfig scoped to that ServiceAccount token (I can walk you through this part separately if needed — it involves extracting the token and building a minimal kubeconfig file).

Step 4: Install the MCP server via Claude Desktop config

Find your config file:

• macOS: ~/Library/Application Support/Claude/claude_desktop_config.json
• Windows: %APPDATA%\Claude\claude_desktop_config.json
• Linux: ~/.config/Claude/claude_desktop_config.json

Add:

{
  "mcpServers": {
    "kubernetes": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "kubernetes-mcp-server@latest", "--read-only"],
      "env": {
        "KUBECONFIG": "/absolute/path/to/eks-readonly.kubeconfig"
      }
    }
  }
}

Step 5: Restart Claude Desktop
Fully quit and reopen. It'll detect the server on startup.

Step 6: Test it
Ask Claude: "List all namespaces in my cluster" or "Show me pods in CrashLoopBackOff across all namespaces."

